00:00:11.170 --> 00:00:13.970 position:66%
Legislation may take one of several forms,

00:00:13.970 --> 00:00:16.410
depending on the intended purpose.

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:19.660 position:66%
Bills and joint resolutions may become law

00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:22.110 position:61%
if enacted during the two-year Congress

00:00:22.110 --> 00:00:23.720
in which they were introduced.

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:29.040 position:97%
Simple resolutions and concurrent resolutions are the other options;

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:33.400 position:97%
these measures cannot make law, but may be used by each chamber,

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:37.130 position:66%
or by both, to publicly express sentiments

00:00:37.130 --> 00:00:39.260 position:58%
or accomplish internal administrative

00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:41.360
or organizational tasks,

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.120 position:75%
such as establishing their rules for proceeding.

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:48.160 position:86%
Only members of each chamber may introduce legislation,

00:00:48.160 --> 00:00:51.340 position:80%
though occasionally a member introduces legislation

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:53.350
by request of the President.

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:58.660 position:97%
Members and their staff typically consult with nonpartisan attorneys

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:03.050 position:92%
in each chamberís Legislative Counsel office for assistance

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:06.360 position:84%
in putting policy proposals into legislative language.

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:10.500 position:70%
Members may circulate the bill and ask others

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:14.970 position:92%
in the chamber ñ often via Dear Colleague letters ñ to sign

00:01:14.970 --> 00:01:17.360 position:56%
on as original co-sponsors of a bill

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:21.240 position:81%
to demonstrate a solid base of support for the idea.

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:25.110 position:83%
In the House, a bill is introduced when it is dropped

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:28.600 position:75%
in the hopper (a wooden box on the House floor).

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:33.860 position:98%
In the Senate, the bill is submitted to clerks on the Senate floor.

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:38.430 position:94%
Upon introduction, the bill will receive a designation based

00:01:38.430 --> 00:01:44.630 position:95%
on the chamber of introduction, for example, H.R. or H.J.Res.

00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:51.250 position:97%
for House-originated bills or joint resolutions and S. or S.J.Res.

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:53.400
for Senate-originated measures.

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:56.100
It will also receive a number,

00:01:56.100 --> 00:01:58.640 position:69%
which typically is the next number available

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:01.690 position:66%
in sequence during that two-year Congress.

00:02:01.690 --> 00:02:07.010 position:83%
In the House, bills then are referred by the Speaker,

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:11.260 position:98%
on the advice of the nonpartisan parliamentarian, to all committees

00:02:11.260 --> 00:02:14.560 position:86%
that have jurisdiction over the provisions in the bill,

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:17.420 position:70%
as determined by the chamberís standing rules

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:19.680
and past referral decisions.

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:24.480 position:88%
Most bills fall under the jurisdiction of one committee.

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:28.030 position:89%
If multiple committees are involved and receive the bill,

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:30.380 position:67%
each committee may work only on the portion

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:32.570
of the bill under its jurisdiction.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:36.990 position:97%
One of those committees will be designated the primary committee

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:39.960 position:70%
of jurisdiction and will likely take the lead

00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:41.750
on any action that may occur.

00:02:41.750 --> 00:02:46.700 position:88%
In the Senate, bills are typically referred to committee

00:02:46.700 --> 00:02:50.220 position:77%
in a similar process, though in almost all cases,

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:53.520 position:94%
the bill is referred to only the committee with jurisdiction

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:57.580 position:70%
over the issue that predominates in the bill.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:02.310 position:97%
In a limited number of cases, a bill might not be referred to committee,

00:03:02.310 --> 00:03:06.000 position:98%
but instead be placed directly on the Senate Calendar of Business

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:19.400 position:78%
through a series of procedural steps on the floor.

